## Users in Linux
Linux is a multi-user operating system.

Each user gets:
- Own files
- Own password
- Own permissions
- Own home directory

Examples:
- kali
- ubuntu
- root

---

## Why Multiple Users?
Different users should have different permissions.

Example:
- Developers
- Admins
- Hackers 😭

All should not get full system access.

---

## Important User Commands

### whoami

Shows current username.

bash
whoami


---

### id

Shows:
- user id
- group id
- permissions

bash
id


---

### cat /etc/passwd

Database of Linux users.

bash
cat /etc/passwd


---

## Creating New User

bash
sudo adduser hacker


### Meaning
Creates new Linux user.

---

## Switching User

bash
su hacker


### Meaning
Switches into another user.

---

## Groups
Groups help manage permissions easily.

Instead of giving permissions one-by-one:
- Create group
- Add users into group

---

## Checking Groups

bash
groups


Shows groups current user belongs to.

---

## Sudo

### SUPER USER DO

sudo gives temporary admin/root powers.

---

## Why sudo Exists?
Normal users should not modify critical system files.

Linux protects system using permissions.

---

## Example Without sudo

bash
apt update


Might give:

bash
Permission denied


---

## Example With sudo

bash
sudo apt update


Now command runs as admin.

---

## Root User

Linux ultimate admin user:

bash
root


Root can:
- modify anything
- delete anything
- install anything

Use carefully 😭🔥

---

## SSH (Secure Shell)

SSH allows connecting one Linux machine to another remotely.

Example:
- Kali → Ubuntu

---

## Installing SSH Server

bash
sudo apt install openssh-server -y


---

## Checking SSH Service

bash
sudo systemctl status ssh


If working:

bash
active (running)


---

## Checking IP Address

bash
ip a


Look for:

bash
inet 10.x.x.x


---

## Connecting Through SSH

From Kali:

bash
ssh username@ip-address


Example:

bash
ssh vboxuser@10.91.171.183


